, Leicestershire, England":"Cossington, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Somerville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from Graveron-Sémerville in Eure (Normandy), from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Sigimar</i> (see   Siemer  ) + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. The surname was taken to Scotland in the 12th century by William <i>de Somerville</i>, a retainer of David, Earl of Huntingdon, who became King David I of Scotland.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Somacháin</b> (see   Summers  ) or <b>Mag Shamradháin</b> (see   Somers  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Siemer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Helmuth, Otto, Theresia.","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Siegmar</i>, composed of the elements <i>sigi</i> ‘victory’ + <i>mari</i>, <i>meri</i> ‘famous’."]},{"name":"Sommerville","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire): variant of   Somerville   1."]},{"name":"Summerville","meanings":["English, Scottish (Lanarkshire), and Irish: variant of   Somerville  . This form of the surname is particularly common in Ireland."]},{"name":"Simrell","meanings":["Scottish: perhaps related to the Ulster name<b>Sumeril</b>, a variant of   Somerville  ."]},{"name":"Summerfield","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>sumor</i> ‘summer’ + <i>feld</i> ‘field, open land’, denoting summer pasture or fields cultivated only in summer, such as Summerfield in Woodnesborough (Kent), Somerfield Court in Sellindge (Kent), and Summerfield in Marlborough (Wiltshire).","English: variant of   Somerville  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Sommerfeld  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When James de Somerville was born about 1280, in Cossington, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Roger de Somerville, was 42 and his mother, Lady Roger de Somerville, was 36. He married Lady James de Somerville in 1320, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1280–":"umbes 1280–Surnud","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1282–Male":"1282–Surnud","1284–Female":"1284–Surnud","1286–Male":"1286–Surnud","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1336–Female":"1336–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1336":"1336","1245":"1245","1320":"1320","Abt 1330":"umbes 1330","1330":"1330","1286":"1286","1240":"1240","1284":"1284","1282":"1282","Abt 1280":"umbes 1280","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cossington, Leicestershire, England":"Cossington, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1280–":"noin 1280–Kuollut","1280–Male":"1280–Kuollut","1282–Male":"1282–Kuollut","1284–Female":"1284–Kuollut","1286–Male":"1286–Kuollut","1290–Female":"1290–Kuollut","1330–Female":"1330–Kuollut","1336–Female":"1336–Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1245–Female":"1245–Kuollut","1336":"1336","1245":"1245","1320":"1320","Abt 1330":"noin 1330","1330":"1330","1286":"1286","1240":"1240","1284":"1284","1282":"1282","Abt 1280":"noin 1280","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cossington, Leicestershire, England":"Cossington, Leicestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1280–":"environ 1280–Décédé","1280–Male":"1280–Décédé","1282–Male":"1282–Décédé","1284–Female":"1284–Décédée","1286–Male":"1286–Décédé","1290–Female":"1290–Décédée","1330–Female":"1330–Décédée","1336–Female":"1336–Décédée","1240–Male":"12